---
import { withBase } from '../../lib/url';
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import QuoteList from '../../components/QuoteList.astro';
import { TECHNIQUES } from '../../lib/techniques';

const t = TECHNIQUES.find((x) => x.slug === 'springing-of-figures')!;
---

<Prose
  title={t.title}
  description={t.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Techniques', href: '/techniques/' }, { name: t.title }]}
  kicker="Technique"
  jsonLd={[{ '@type': 'Article', headline: t.title }]}
>
  <p>
    Because the later figures of a chart are generated from the earlier ones, the same figure often
    appears in several houses. The springing of a figure is this passing from one house into
    another. It extends a reading, since the houses into which a significator springs name the
    persons and matters caught up in the affair.
  </p>

  <h2>Trace a springing</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Take a significator and find every other house where its figure appears.</li>
    <li>Read each passage as one movement, from the house it starts in to the house where it comes to rest, not as several separate findings.</li>
    <li>Judge by the house the figure reaches and by the figure's own quality, good or ill.</li>
    <li>Treat a springing as a circumstance of the matter. It adds detail, but it does not join the significators or settle the answer by itself.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>In the sources</h2>
  <QuoteList topic="springing" noFigures />
  <p>
    Cattan and Heydon also give the meaning of each figure's passing house by house, quoted on
    each <a href={withBase('/figures/')}>figure's own page</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Thus in Agrippa's example, the figure of the second house (money) found again in the sixth
    (servants) shows a thief within the household. Crowley applies the same rule in his worked
    example: see <a href={withBase('/library/crowley/method-of-judging/')}>the General Method of Judging a
    Figure</a>.
  </p>
</Prose>
